    "html": "<p>If you&#39;ve searched for help with detransition or transition regret, you may have run into a confusing mix of strong opinions. It can be hard to find a simple, honest answer to a basic question: <em>what does this kind of therapy actually involve?</em></p>\n<p>Let me try to answer that plainly.</p>\n<h2>Support that follows your goals</h2>\n<p>Detransition and transition-regret support is <strong>voluntary, client-led talk therapy</strong>. That means a few specific things:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>You set the goals.</strong> I don&#39;t arrive with an agenda for your life or your body. My role is to understand what <em>you</em> want and to walk alongside you toward it.</li>\n<li><strong>You set the pace.</strong> You can explore something, pause, change direction, or stop entirely. Nothing happens without your readiness.</li>\n<li><strong>It&#39;s trauma-informed.</strong> We prioritize safety, trust, and choice — the foundations of any ethical therapeutic relationship.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This is the same client-centered approach that defines good therapy for grief, trauma, or any other deeply personal struggle.</p>\n<h2>What it is <em>not</em></h2>\n<p>It is <strong>not</strong> &quot;conversion therapy.&quot; It does not try to change anyone&#39;s identity, and it never pressures you toward a predetermined outcome. There is no &quot;fixing,&quot; no &quot;curing,&quot; and no script you&#39;re expected to follow.</p>\n<p>That distinction matters ethically and legally — but more than that, it matters <em>for you</em>. Coercion has no place in healing. A space that pushes you toward someone else&#39;s conclusion isn&#39;t a safe one.</p>\n<h2>Why people seek this kind of support</h2>\n<p>People come to detransition support for many reasons: grief over time or relationships, questions about identity, the physical and emotional weight of medical decisions, or a desire to reconnect with their faith. Some want to talk through regret. Some are simply looking for a therapist who won&#39;t judge them for asking hard questions.</p>\n<p>Whatever brings you in, you deserve a licensed clinician who will listen without an agenda.</p>\n<h2>A therapist who has walked this road</h2>\n<p>I transitioned from female to male and later made the decision to detransition. Because I&#39;ve lived through these questions myself, I can hold space for the grief and identity struggles that can come with them — with empathy rather than judgment. You can <a href=\"/about\">read more of my story</a>.</p>\n<p>If any of this resonates, you&#39;re welcome to <a href=\"/contact\">reach out</a> for a confidential, no-pressure conversation. This is your journey, and your goals lead the way.</p>\n"
