    "html": "<p>Some wounds come from what happened to us. Others come from what <em>didn&#39;t</em> happen — the comfort that never came, the feelings no one asked about, the sense that our inner world simply didn&#39;t register. This is <strong>childhood emotional neglect</strong> (CEN), and because it&#39;s defined by absence, it&#39;s remarkably easy to overlook.</p>\n<h2>Why it&#39;s so hard to name</h2>\n<p>People who grew up with emotional neglect often say things like, <em>&quot;I had a fine childhood — nothing bad happened.&quot;</em> And often, on the surface, that&#39;s true. There may have been no abuse, no obvious trauma.</p>\n<p>But when a child&#39;s emotions are consistently ignored, dismissed, or left unattended, they learn a quiet lesson: <em>my feelings don&#39;t matter.</em> That lesson can shape an entire adult life.</p>\n<h2>Common signs in adulthood</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>A persistent sense of emptiness or feeling &quot;different,&quot; without knowing why</li>\n<li>Difficulty identifying or trusting your own emotions</li>\n<li>Being hard on yourself; a harsh inner critic</li>\n<li>Discomfort relying on others, or guilt when you have needs</li>\n<li>A tendency toward people-pleasing or over-responsibility (sometimes called <a href=\"/services/codependency-therapy\">codependency</a>)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If several of these feel familiar, you&#39;re not broken — and you&#39;re not alone.</p>\n<h2>Healing begins with permission</h2>\n<p>The good news is that what was missed can, in many ways, be learned later. Healing from CEN often involves:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Learning to notice and name your emotions without judgment</li>\n<li>Building self-compassion to soften the inner critic</li>\n<li>Practicing healthy boundaries and allowing yourself to have needs</li>\n<li>Grieving what wasn&#39;t there, so it stops quietly running the show</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For those who want it, faith can be a steadying part of that work — grounding your worth in being loved as you are, not in what you do for others.</p>\n<p>This is gentle, paced work, and it&#39;s very possible. If it resonates, you can explore <a href=\"/services/trauma-ptsd-therapy\">trauma-informed therapy</a> or simply <a href=\"/contact\">reach out</a> to talk.</p>\n"
